herine Trundle argues that charity and philanthropy are the central means by which many American women negotiate a sense of migrant belonging in Italy. This book traces women’s daily acts of charity as they gave food to the poor, fundraised among the wealthy, monitored untrustworthy recipients, assessed the needy, and reflected on the emotional work that charity required. In exploring the often-ignored role of charitable action in migrant community formation, Trundle contributes to anthropological theories of gift giving, compassion, and reflexivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAmericansxCultural assimilationzItalyzTuscany. 0aAmericanszItalyzTuscanyxSocial conditions. 0aAssimilation (Sociology)zItalyzTuscany. 0aCompassionzItalyzTuscany. 0aImmigrantsxCultural assimilationzItalyzTuscany. 0aSocial integrationzItalyzTuscay. 0aSocial integration. 0aSocial servicezItalyzTuscany. 0aWomen immigrantszItalyzTuscanyxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311099823840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238370340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782383703423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782383703/original  a978-3-11-099823-8  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK